{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox ancient site | name = Chandavaram Buddhist site | native_name = | native_name_lang = | alternate_name = Chandavaram excavation site | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | map = | map_type = India Andhra Pradesh | map_alt = | map_caption = Location on [[Andhra Pradesh]] map | map_size = | relief = | coordinates = {{coord|15|55|58.5156|N|79|25|40.2240|E|display=inline,title}} | map_dot_label = | location = [[Chandavaram]] village | region = [[Andhra Pradesh]] | type = [[Buddhist]] [[Excavation (archaeology)|excavation]] site | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | volume = | diameter = | circumference = | height = | builder = [[Satavahana dynasty]]<ref name="Chandavaram – Foothold of Buddhist Mahastupa">{{cite news|title=Chandavaram – Foothold of Buddhist Mahastupa|publisher=kostalife.com|accessdate=Dec 2015|url=http://www.kostalife.com/heritage/chandavaram-foothold-of-buddhist-mahastupa-in-andhra/}}</ref>| material = [[Limestone]] | built = 2 century [[Before Christ|BCE]] to 2 century [[Common Era|CE]] | abandoned = | epochs = <!-- actually displays as "Periods" --> | cultures = [[Culture of Buddhism|Buddhist]] | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations = 1964 | archaeologists = [[Dr. (title)|Dr.]] Veluri Venkata Krishna Sastry | condition = Restored | ownership = Public | management = | public_access = Yes | other_designation = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | notes = }} {{Buddhism}}
'''Chandavaram Buddhist site''' is an ancient [[Buddhist]] site in [[Chandavaram]] village in [[Prakasam district]] in the [[India]]n state of [[Andhra Pradesh]].<ref name="Easy pickings"/><ref name="About Chandavaram Excavation Site">{{cite news|title=About Chandavaram Excavation Site|publisher=Holidayiq.com|accessdate=Dec 2015|url=http://www.holidayiq.com/Chandavaram-Excavation-Site-Ongole-Sightseeing-857-18953.html}}</ref> Situated on the bank of [[Gundlakamma River]], the site is {{convert|10|km|mi}} northwest of [[Donakonda railway station]].<ref name="Chandavaram monastic cluster">{{cite news|title=Chandavaram monastic cluster|publisher=Monastic Asia|accessdate=Dec 2015|url=http://monastic-asia.wikidot.com/chandavaram}}</ref> The Chandavaram Buddhist site was built between the 2nd century [[Before Christ|BCE]] and the 2nd century [[Common Era|CE]] during the [[Satavahana dynasty]] and was discovered by [[Dr. (title)|Dr.]] Veluri Venkata Krishna Sastry in 1964.<ref name="Chandavaram – Foothold of Buddhist Mahastupa"/><ref name="Easy pickings">{{cite news|title=Easy pickings|work=[[India Today]]|accessdate=Dec 2015|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/series-of-robberies-at-remote-buddhist-sites-in-andhra-pradesh-exposes-neglect-of-excavated-treasures/1/230807.html}}</ref><ref name="Chandavaram Buddhist site">{{cite news|title=Chandavaram Buddhist site|publisher=Discovered India|accessdate=Dec 2015|url=http://www.discoveredindia.com/andhra-pradesh/attractions/buddhist-centers/chandavaram-buddhist-site.htm}}</ref>
==History== The first of its kind in the state of [[Andhra Pradesh]], the Chandavaram Buddhist site was constructed between the 2nd century [[Before Christ|BCE]] and the 2nd century [[Common Era|CE]]. It was an active center for [[Buddhist]] religious activities, and was also inhabited at the time.<ref name="About Chandavaram Excavation Site"/><ref name="Chandavaram Buddhist site"/> The age of the site was determined by the [[Radiocarbon dating|carbon dating]] of [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]] discovered during [[Excavation (archaeology)|excavation]]. The sculptural panels in the site are of the [[Amarāvatī mahācetiya#Amaravati School|Amaravati school]] which also suggests that the site was built between the 2nd century [[Before Christ|BCE]] and the 2nd century [[Common Era|CE]].<ref name="Chandavaram – Foothold of Buddhist Mahastupa"/> The Chandavaram Buddhist site was used as a resting place by [[Buddhist monk]]s traveling from [[Varanasi|Kashi]] to [[Kanchipuram|Kanchi]].<ref name="Chandavaram Buddhist site"/> Discovered in 1964, the site was constructed during the [[Satavahana dynasty]].<ref name="Easy pickings"/> [[Ayaka pillars]] are absent from the site, indicating that the [[Hinayana]] form of [[Buddhism]] was prevalent in [[Chandavaram]].<ref name="Chandavaram, Andhra Pradesh">{{cite news|title=Chandavaram, Andhra Pradesh|publisher=Buddhist tourism|accessdate=Dec 2015|url=http://www.buddhist-tourism.com/countries/india/buddhist-sites/chandavaram-andhra-pradesh.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923195013/http://www.buddhist-tourism.com/countries/india/buddhist-sites/chandavaram-andhra-pradesh.html#|archive-date=23 September 2015|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The site houses a double terraced [[Stupa|MahaStupa]] on a hilltop which is next in importance only to [[Sanchi Stupa]]. The hill on which the MahaStupa is located is called Singarakonda.<ref name="Chandavaram – Foothold of Buddhist Mahastupa"/><ref name="Chandavaram, Andhra Pradesh"/>
==Construction and structure== Constructed during the [[Satavahana dynasty]], the Chandavaram Buddhist site houses a double terraced [[Stupa|MahaStupa]] built on an elevated platform situated on a hilltop.<ref name="Chandavaram – Foothold of Buddhist Mahastupa"/><ref name="About Chandavaram Excavation Site"/><ref name="Chandavaram, Andhra Pradesh"/> The MahaStupa exhibits the characteristics of stupas built under the [[Hinayana]] form of [[Buddhism]]. The main dome (MahaStupa) is {{convert|120|ft|m}} in circumference and {{convert|30|ft|m}} high. It has carved panels that portray the [[Dharmachakra]] (the wheel of ''[[Dharma]]'', one of the [[Ashtamangala]] of [[Indian religions]] such as [[Hinduism]], [[Jainism]] and [[Buddhism]]). Apart from the main stupa, the site also houses several [[Vihara]]s, [[Brahmi script|Brahmi inscriptions]] and other stupas. In the MahaStupa, there is a [[Chaitya|Maha Chaitya]] which is {{convert|1.6|m|feet}} high and {{convert|60|cm|feet}} wide.<ref name="About Chandavaram Excavation Site"/><ref name="Chandavaram Buddhist site"/>
The MahaStupa resembles the [[Dharmarajika|Dharmarajika stupa]] in [[Taxila]], [[Pakistan]]. The panels on the MahaStupa are made of [[limestone]]. The panels and the drum sections of the MahaStupa exhibit the [[Buddha footprint]], Stupas, [[Bodhi tree]]s and also narratives in the form of [[Jataka tales]] along with other stories. Since 1964, the Chandavaram Buddhist site has been excavated four times, and fifteen regular-sized and approximately one hundred small [[stupa]]s have been discovered. The site comprises the following:<ref name="Chandavaram – Foothold of Buddhist Mahastupa"/>
{{Div col}} *[[Stupa|Main Stupa]] (MahaStupa) *[[Chaitya|Maha Chaitya]] *[[Museum]] *Silamandapa *[[Vihara]] *[[Votive offering|Votive Stupas]] {{div col end}}
[[File:Hyderabad Dec2011 15.JPG|thumb|260px|left|Buddha statue, now at the [[Hussain Sagar]], [[Hyderabad]].]]
===Monolith statue of Buddha=== In 1985, a project called the "Buddha Poornima Project" was proposed. Under this project, the world's tallest standing [[monolith]] statue of [[Buddha]] was to be erected on the site. Made out of [[granite]], the statue was carved by 200 sculptors in two years and on completion it weighed 440 tonnes with an overall height of {{convert|17|m|feet}}. However, the [[Buddha Statue of Hyderabad|Buddha statue]] was transported to city of [[Hyderabad]] in 1988 instead, where it was erected in 1992 in the [[Hussain sagar lake]] and stands today.<ref name="Chandavaram – Foothold of Buddhist Mahastupa"/><ref name="Buddha of the lake bottom">{{cite news|title=Buddha of the lake bottom|work=Washington Post|accessdate=Dec 2015|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1990/04/09/buddha-of-the-lake-bottom/342902b7-7025-41d3-a856-c14c1fac3815/}}</ref><ref name="Buddha statue consecrated">{{cite news|title=Buddha statue consecrated|work=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=Dec 2015|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/article3234728.ece}}</ref>
==Archeological findings== One [[Stupa|MahaStupa]], fifteen regular-sized and approximately one hundred small [[Stupa]]s have been discovered in the Chandavaram Buddhist site. Apart from the [[Chaitya|Maha Chaitya]], Silamandapa, [[Vihara]] and the [[Votive offering|Votive Stupas]], more than two dozen "Buddhist slabs" (decorated with designs and inscriptions) have also been discovered.<ref name="Chandavaram Buddhist site"/>
==Pilferage== Pilferage of artifacts has been reported at the Chandavaram Buddhist site since the year 2000. In Oct 2000, two {{convert|9|feet}} long panels, with engravings of the [[Bodhi tree]] and of the Chaitra were uprooted from a cement platform and stolen from the site's museum.<ref name="Easy pickings"/> In February 2001, three pillars, each measuring {{convert|9|feet}} long and including one in which the [[Buddha]] was represented as fire were stolen.<ref name="Easy pickings"/> In March 2001, three more ornate pillars and a lotus [[medallion]] were stolen.<ref name="Easy pickings"/>
